01:18:53.786 --> 01:18:57.380
Of course, and that's my
last comment for today,

01:18:57.380 --> 01:18:59.790
if you have a spheric
quadrupole trap

01:18:59.790 --> 01:19:04.150
and you go right
through the origin,

01:19:04.150 --> 01:19:06.970
you're out of luck
because here, the atom

01:19:06.970 --> 01:19:09.040
sees the magnetic field is down.

01:19:09.040 --> 01:19:10.506
It gets smaller,
the magnetic field

01:19:10.506 --> 01:19:11.630
gets smaller, gets smaller.

01:19:11.630 --> 01:19:13.270
The magnet field gets zero.

01:19:13.270 --> 01:19:16.600
Oopsy, the magnetic field
points in the other direction.

01:19:16.600 --> 01:19:18.050
And there was no warning.

01:19:18.050 --> 01:19:22.600
The magnetic field has jumped
from 0 degree to 180 degree.

01:19:22.600 --> 01:19:27.260
There was never, ever any
transverse field around which

01:19:27.260 --> 01:19:30.360
the atom could precess and
change its orientation.

01:19:30.360 --> 01:19:33.580
So therefore, when an atom is
aligned with a magnetic field

01:19:33.580 --> 01:19:36.590
moves through the origin,
oopsy, it's anti aligned.

01:19:36.590 --> 01:19:40.280
It has lost its orientation with
respect to the magnetic field,

01:19:40.280 --> 01:19:43.610
and this is the breakdown
of rapid adiabatic passage

01:19:43.610 --> 01:19:45.230
because there's no adiabadicity.

01:19:45.230 --> 01:19:47.770
It is not an adiabatic
change of the direction

01:19:47.770 --> 01:19:50.210
of the magnetic field,
it's a sudden field.

01:19:50.210 --> 01:19:52.310
And the consequences are bad.

01:19:52.310 --> 01:19:54.580
You lose your atoms
from the magnetic trap.

01:19:54.580 --> 01:19:56.207
It's called Majorana losses.

